{
    "analysis": "None",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file, return a compact summary containing: 1) total row count, 2) minimum and maximum timestamp, 3) up to 50 distinct cmdb_id values (or all if fewer), and 4) up to 50 distinct KPI/feature names (for metric.csv use the 'kpi_name' column, for trace.csv use 'trace_name', for log.csv use 'log_name', for error_logs.csv list distinct values from the 'message' column instead). Return results as a small table per file (limit displayed rows) and do not print full raw datasets." 
}

{
    "analysis": "We have basic file-level summaries from the Executor: metric.csv (148,332 rows; covers 2022-03-21 11:00–11:29+08:00; 59 distinct cmdb_id; 1,228 distinct kpi_name), trace.csv (34,304 rows; covers the same time window; 40 cmdb_id; ~200 trace features), log.csv (1,758 rows; 31 cmdb_id; 2 log feature names), and error_logs.csv (1,708 rows; 3 cmdb_id; many textual messages mentioning failures for frontend pods). These summaries confirm the telemetry covers the incident window and that metric data is rich (many KPIs and components) — metric analysis should be used first to narrow down faulty components and timepoints. No anomaly-level analysis has been performed yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair: 1) compute the global P95 threshold using the full available time series in metric.csv (do NOT filter by incident time when computing P95). 2) Filter metric rows to the incident window from '2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00' to '2022-03-21T11:30:00+08:00' (inclusive). 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: the number of points in the incident window with value >= P95 (anomaly_count), the earliest anomaly timestamp in ASIA/Shanghai, and the maximum value observed in the window. 4) Return a table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) rows ordered by anomaly_count descending, but include only rows with anomaly_count > 0. Columns to return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_threshold, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai, max_value_in_window. Store full intermediate grouped results in a kernel variable but limit displayed rows to at most 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous metric grouping results (kernel variables grouped_all and result_top20) we observed clear signals: many container-level KPIs for shippingservice2-0 have anomaly_count=30 with earliest anomaly at 2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00, while a cluster of mesh-related KPIs for checkoutservice-2 show anomaly_count=21 with earliest anomaly at 2022-03-21T11:09:00+08:00. This suggests at least two distinct anomaly clusters: one starting at ~11:00 (shippingservice2-0) and another starting at ~11:09 (checkoutservice-2 / related mesh metrics). To decide root cause components and times we need to aggregate anomalies per component and inspect the earliest anomaly timestamp and breadth of affected KPIs per component (to distinguish single-KPI noise vs broad faults). Next I will request a compact per-component aggregate (counts, earliest time, KPI examples) so we can pick top candidates for deeper trace and log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the existing kernel variable `grouped_all` (the per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) table with p95_threshold, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai, max_value_in_window), aggregate by cmdb_id as follows: 1) compute distinct_anomalous_kpi_count = number of kpi_name with anomaly_count>0; 2) sum_anomaly_points = sum of anomaly_count across those kpi_names; 3) earliest_anomaly_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai = minimum earliest_anomaly_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai among that component's anomalous KPIs; 4) collect up to 5 example kpi_name samples (only those with anomaly_count>0) as a comma-separated string. Return the top 20 components ordered by distinct_anomalous_kpi_count descending, then sum_anomaly_points descending. Columns to display: cmdb_id, distinct_anomalous_kpi_count, sum_anomaly_points, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai, example_kpi_samples. Store the full aggregated table in a kernel variable named `component_anom_summary` but limit displayed rows to at most 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the component-level metric aggregation the system shows two notable anomaly clusters: a very large set of anomalies across many services/pods beginning at 2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00 (affecting adservice, adservice2, frontend pods, many services — suggesting a broad resource or node-related event at window start). The earlier metric-group scan also showed a concentrated set of anomalies for shippingservice2-0 with anomaly_count=30 and earliest 11:00, and another cluster of mesh-related KPIs for checkoutservice-2 with earliest anomalies around 11:09. This implies there may be at least two distinct incidents during the 11:00—11:30 window: one starting at ~11:00 that is widespread and likely node/resource-level, and a second around ~11:09 that involves mesh/checkoutservice metrics. We still need trace-level signals to decide which service/pod is the downstream faulty component for the second incident and logs/error_logs to identify the exact failure reason(s). Next step: analyze trace telemetry to find trace features that become anomalous in the window and their earliest timestamps to help localize downstream faulty components.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) pair: 1) compute the global P95 threshold using the full available series for that pair (do NOT filter by incident window when computing P95). 2) Filter trace rows to the incident window '2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00' through '2022-03-21T11:30:00+08:00' (inclusive). 3) For each pair compute: p95_threshold, anomaly_count = number of points in the window with value >= P95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai (if anomaly_count>0), and max_value_in_window. 4) Return a compact table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs ordered by anomaly_count descending, but include only pairs with anomaly_count > 0. Columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95_threshold, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai, max_value_in_window. Store the full grouped trace results in kernel variable `grouped_trace_all` and the returned top-20 in `result_trace_top20`. Limit displayed rows to at most 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis computed global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) and then flagged anomalies within the incident window. The result shows many trace features with p95_threshold = 0.0, causing anomaly_count = 30 and earliest anomaly = 2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00 for many trace pairs (notably many error_rate and duration_p95 metrics from frontend->services). This reinforces that a widespread anomaly began at the window start (11:00+08:00). However, P95=0.0 for many trace features reduces their discriminative power (they flag any non-negative value), so traces alone are noisy for identifying the precise downstream faulty component. Metric aggregation earlier indicated two distinct clusters: a broad set of anomalies starting at 11:00 affecting many services/pods (including strong node/container KPIs, e.g., container.node-5/* and shippingservice2-0 container metrics), and a second cluster with mesh-related checkoutservice-2 anomalies around 11:09. To disambiguate the two failures and determine exact root cause components and times, we now need compact log-level evidence (error_logs and normalized log metrics) to pinpoint which component(s) show errors and their first occurrence times. No final root-cause determination yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze error_logs.csv and log.csv for compact evidence: \n1) error_logs.csv: For each cmdb_id compute total_message_count (over full file), earliest_message_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai, latest_message_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai, and provide up to 5 sample message texts per cmdb_id. Return rows sorted by total_message_count descending, limit to top 20. Store full table in kernel variable `error_log_summary`.\n2) log.csv: For each (cmdb_id, log_name) pair compute the global P95 threshold using the full series (do NOT filter by incident window), then filter log rows to the incident window '2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00' through '2022-03-21T11:30:00+08:00' (inclusive). For each pair compute: p95_threshold, anomaly_count = number of points in the window with value >= P95, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai (if anomaly_count>0), and max_value_in_window. Return only rows with anomaly_count>0, sorted by anomaly_count desc, limit to top 20. Store full result in kernel variable `log_metric_anom`.\nReturn both compact tables (error_log_summary and log_metric_anom) in the Executor output."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step produced candidate_component_details for three strong candidates: node-5, shippingservice2-0, and checkoutservice-2. Summaries show all three have many anomalous KPIs and earliest anomalies at 2022-03-21T11:00:00+08:00. node-5 shows disk/system filesystem KPIs among its top samples and a very large total anomaly point count, suggesting a node-level resource problem centered on node-5 at the incident window start. shippingservice2-0’s top KPIs reference container.node-5 metrics (indicating it was scheduled on node-5). checkoutservice-2 has many anomalies too; earlier trace aggregation suggested a separate mesh-related cluster around ~11:09, but candidate details still list earliest anomaly at 11:00 for some KPIs — this likely means different KPIs per component breached thresholds at different times. We are not yet certain of the precise root-cause KPI type (CPU, memory, disk, or network) for each of the two failures, nor the exact first-occurrence timestamp per root cause. To decide the root cause reason we must compute KPI-level severity (how far a KPI exceeded its P95) per candidate and inspect the most severely breached KPIs and their earliest breach timestamps. This will allow us to (A) confirm whether node-5 resource KPIs (CPU/memory/disk/network) are the primary cause at ~11:00, and (B) determine whether checkoutservice-2’s failure is a separate mesh/network issue around ~11:09 or part of the same node-level event.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the stored metric grouping table `grouped_all`, for each candidate component ['node-5','shippingservice2-0','checkoutservice-2'] do the following: 1) select rows where cmdb_id equals the candidate and anomaly_count>0. 2) For each selected row compute: p95_threshold, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai, max_value_in_window, and relative_breach defined as (max_value_in_window - p95_threshold) / max(abs(p95_threshold), 1e-9). 3) Return the top 10 kpi_name rows per component ordered by relative_breach descending. 4) Also provide a one-line aggregate for each component: total distinct_anomalous_kpi_count (count of selected rows), sum_anomaly_points (sum of anomaly_count), and the minimum earliest_anomaly_timestamp_ASIA/Shanghai across its selected rows. Store the full per-candidate KPI-level table in kernel variable `candidate_kpi_severity` and the aggregates in `candidate_kpi_aggregates`. Limit displayed rows to at most 30 (10 per component)."
}

I reviewed the metric, trace, and log analyses. Two distinct failures are supported by the telemetry: an early severe network spike at 11:00 affecting shippingservice2-0 (scheduled on node-5), and a later severe mesh/network spike affecting checkoutservice-2 around 11:07–11:09. Below are the decisive root-cause selections.

